
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lzip` baraye moteghassed kardan (compress) ya baz kardan (decompress) file-ha estefade mishavad. `lzip.lzip` neshan dahande in ast ke file ya pooshe ba estefade az `lzip` moteghassed shode ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lzip -d file.lzip`  --> 🔓 Baz kardan file `file.lzip`
    🔹 `lzip -k file`  --> 🧱 Moteghassed kardan `file` va negah dashtane asle file (keep)
    🔹 `lzip -z file`  --> 🧱 Moteghassed kardan `file` (hamoon `lzip file` ham mishe)
    🔹 `lzip -o output file` --> 💾 Moshakhas kardane esme file khorooji

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lzip file.txt

    🔹 File `file.txt` moteghassed mishe va mishe `file.txt.lz`.

    $ lzip -d file.txt.lz

    🔹 File `file.txt.lz` baz mishe va mishe `file.txt`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lzip -k file.txt

    🔹 `file.txt` moteghassed mishe be `file.txt.lz`, vali `file.txt` ham pak nemishe va mimone.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lzip` command is used to compress or decompress files. `lzip.lzip` indicates that a file or directory has been compressed using `lzip`.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lzip -d file.lzip`  --> 🔓 Decompress `file.lzip`
    🔹 `lzip -k file`  --> 🧱 Compress `file` and keep the original file
    🔹 `lzip -z file`  --> 🧱 Compress `file` (same as `lzip file`)
    🔹 `lzip -o output file` --> 💾 Specify the output file name

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lzip file.txt

    🔹 Compresses `file.txt` and creates `file.txt.lz`.

    $ lzip -d file.txt.lz

    🔹 Decompresses `file.txt.lz` and creates `file.txt`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lzip -k file.txt

    🔹 `file.txt` is compressed to `file.txt.lz`, but the original `file.txt` is not deleted and remains.
